    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="background">
A well-designed user interface must share a common set of Â“usability heuristics,&quot; which contribute to effective use of the application.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="13" relname="span"> Some of these heuristics include:</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="14" relname="span">
 
1. Consistency can greatly facilitate the learning of a new user interface</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="8" relname="volitional-cause"> because it allows users to transfer existing knowledge in order to predict how to do things they have never done before.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="11" relname="span"> 

2. Error Recovery, the extent to which an application tolerates common and unavoidable human error and allows for easy recovery from any undesired actions taken by the user.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="elaboration"> Many users learn applications and user interfaces through interactive discovery.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="10" relname="list"> 

3. Familiarity refers to the extent that the user interface provides elements and actions that follow real-world conventions.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="10" relname="list"> 

4. User Control, a usable and effective user interface puts the user in charge of the application, thereby allowing the user to initiate all actions, rather than being controlled and directed by the application.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="10" relname="list"> 

5. Flexibility is the extent to which a user interface accommodates for variations in user skill and preferences.</segment>
